### Styling Text and Fonts in CSS

In CSS, you can control the appearance of text and fonts using a variety of properties. These properties allow you to define how text looks, including the type of font, size, weight, color, alignment, and more. Here are some of the key CSS properties for styling text:

- **`font-family`**: Specifies the font for an element. You can use generic family names (like `serif` or `sans-serif`) or specific font names.
- **`font-size`**: Sets the size of the text, which can be defined in pixels (`px`), ems (`em`), rems (`rem`), or percentages (`%`).
- **`font-weight`**: Defines the thickness of the font. Common values include `normal`, `bold`, `bolder`, and numeric values (100 to 900).
- **`text-align`**: Aligns the text within its container. Possible values include `left`, `right`, `center`, and `justify`.
- **`color`**: Sets the color of the text.

### Example HTML Document Demonstrating Text Properties

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Text and Font Styling Example</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif; /* Default font for the body */
            background-color: #f4f4f4; /* Light background color */
            color: #333; /* Dark gray text color */
            line-height: 1.6; /* Increased line height for better readability */
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }

        h1 {
            font-size: 36px; /* Font size for h1 */
            font-weight: bold; /* Bold font weight */
            text-align: center; /* Centered heading */
            color: #2c3e50; /* Darker color for heading */
        }

        h2 {
            font-size: 28px; /* Font size for h2 */
            font-weight: 600; /* Semi-bold font weight */
            text-align: left; /* Left-aligned heading */
            color: #2980b9; /* Blue color for h2 */
        }

        p {
            font-size: 18px; /* Font size for paragraphs */
            font-weight: normal; /* Normal font weight */
            text-align: justify; /* Justified text */
            margin: 10px 0; /* Margin between paragraphs */
        }

        a {
            font-size: 18px; /* Font size for links */
            font-weight: bold; /* Bold links */
            color: #e74c3c; /* Red color for links */
            text-decoration: none; /* Remove underline */
        }

        a:hover {
            text-decoration: underline; /* Underline links on hover */
            color: #c0392b; /* Darker red on hover */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Styling Text and Fonts in CSS</h1>
    <h2>Subheading Example</h2>
    <p>This is an example paragraph demonstrating how to style text in CSS. You can set different properties like font size, weight, and alignment to enhance the readability and visual appeal of your content.</p>
    <p>Links are also styled to be bold and change color on hover. This helps users know they can interact with them.</p>
    <p>For more information, visit <a href="https://example.com" target="_blank">this link</a>.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of CSS Text Properties Used

1. **Body Styles**:
   - `font-family: Arial, sans-serif;`: Sets the default font for the body to Arial, falling back to a generic sans-serif font if Arial is unavailable.
   - `background-color: #f4f4f4;`: Applies a light gray background color to the entire page.
   - `color: #333;`: Sets the default text color to dark gray for better readability.
   - `line-height: 1.6;`: Increases the line height for improved readability between lines of text.
   - `margin: 0; padding: 20px;`: Removes default margins and adds padding to the body.

2. **Heading 1 Styles (`h1`)**:
   - `font-size: 36px;`: Sets the font size for the main heading.
   - `font-weight: bold;`: Applies a bold font weight to the heading.
   - `text-align: center;`: Centers the heading within the page.
   - `color: #2c3e50;`: Uses a darker blue-gray color for the heading.

3. **Heading 2 Styles (`h2`)**:
   - `font-size: 28px;`: Sets the font size for subheadings.
   - `font-weight: 600;`: Applies a semi-bold font weight.
   - `text-align: left;`: Aligns the subheading to the left.
   - `color: #2980b9;`: Applies a blue color to the subheading.

4. **Paragraph Styles (`p`)**:
   - `font-size: 18px;`: Sets the font size for paragraphs.
   - `font-weight: normal;`: Applies a normal font weight to the text.
   - `text-align: justify;`: Justifies the text, aligning both the left and right edges.
   - `margin: 10px 0;`: Adds vertical margins between paragraphs.

5. **Link Styles (`a`)**:
   - `font-size: 18px;`: Sets the font size for links.
   - `font-weight: bold;`: Makes the links bold.
   - `color: #e74c3c;`: Sets the link color to red.
   - `text-decoration: none;`: Removes the underline from links.

6. **Link Hover Styles (`a:hover`)**:
   - `text-decoration: underline;`: Underlines links when hovered.
   - `color: #c0392b;`: Changes the link color to a darker red on hover.

### Conclusion

Styling text and fonts in CSS involves using various properties to control the appearance of text elements such as headings, paragraphs, and links. By using these properties, you can enhance the readability and visual appeal of your content, making it more engaging for users.